<Layout title="Section 4 – Personal Hygiene">
  <h1>Section 4: Personal Hygiene</h1>
  <p><em>Competency 7093.4.4 – Demonstrates Daily Personal Hygiene Practices</em></p>
  <p>
    Perform personal hygiene (bed baths, oral hygiene) in the laboratory setting. Assess
    skin and detect abnormalities during hygiene care.
  </p>

  <h2>Bed Baths</h2>
  <h3>Types of Baths</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Complete bed bath:</strong> Nurse performs all bathing for a fully dependent patient.</li>
    <li><strong>Partial bed bath:</strong> Patient performs part; nurse assists with areas they cannot reach.</li>
    <li><strong>Disposable bed bath:</strong> Pre-moistened, disposable cloths; no rinsing required.</li>
    <li><strong>Tub bath / shower:</strong> For ambulatory patients who can safely use these facilities.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>General Bathing Principles</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Maintain privacy and dignity throughout.</li>
    <li>Use warm water (105–115 °F / 41–46 °C); verify temperature.</li>
    <li>Wash from clean to dirty areas; wash perineum last.</li>
    <li>Assess skin condition (color, integrity, lesions, pressure injuries) during the bath.</li>
    <li>Keep patient covered to prevent chilling and protect dignity.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Oral Hygiene</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Perform oral care at least twice daily.</li>
    <li>Unconscious/ventilated patients: Use CHG oral rinse per protocol — prevents ventilator-associated pneumonia (VAP).</li>
    <li>Assess for oral lesions, dryness, bleeding gums, and denture fit.</li>
    <li>Position patient upright (HOB ≥ 30°) to prevent aspiration during oral care.</li>
    <li>Denture care: Remove, rinse, and clean; store in labeled container with water when not worn.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Hair, Nail &amp; Foot Care</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Assess scalp for lesions, dryness, and lice (pediculosis capitis).</li>
    <li>Comb or brush gently, detangling from ends toward the scalp.</li>
    <li>Nail care: Trim fingernails straight across and smooth edges.</li>
    <li>Do <strong>not</strong> cut toenails of diabetic patients or those with peripheral vascular disease — refer to podiatry.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Skin Integrity &amp; Pressure Injury Assessment</h2>
  <p>
    Assess skin during each hygiene encounter. Use the <strong>Braden Scale</strong> to
    identify patients at risk for pressure injuries.
  </p>
  <h3>Braden Scale Subscales</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Subscale</th><th>Score Range</th><th>Focus</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Sensory perception</td><td>1–4</td><td>Ability to respond to pressure-related discomfort</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Moisture</td><td>1–4</td><td>Degree of skin exposure to moisture</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Activity</td><td>1–4</td><td>Degree of physical activity</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Mobility</td><td>1–4</td><td>Ability to change/control body position</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Nutrition</td><td>1–4</td><td>Usual food intake pattern</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Friction &amp; shear</td><td>1–3</td><td>Risk from friction and shear forces</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>Total score ≤ 18 = at risk; ≤ 12 = high risk; ≤ 9 = very high risk.</p>

  <h3>Pressure Injury Staging</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Stage</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Stage I</td><td>Non-blanchable erythema of intact skin</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage II</td><td>Partial-thickness skin loss; shallow open ulcer or intact/ruptured blister</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage III</td><td>Full-thickness skin loss; subcutaneous fat visible</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Stage IV</td><td>Full-thickness tissue loss exposing bone, tendon, or muscle</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Unstageable</td><td>Full-thickness loss covered by slough or eschar; depth unknown</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Deep Tissue Injury (DTI)</td><td>Purple/maroon intact or non-intact skin; blood-filled blister</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Essential Lessons (Sherpath, Section 4 – Chapter 40)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Overview of the Integumentary System and Mucous Membranes</li>
    <li>Integumentary System: Assess and Recognize Cues</li>
    <li>Integumentary System: Analyze Cues and Prioritize Hypothesis; Plan and Generate Solutions</li>
    <li>Integumentary System: Implement and Take Action; Evaluate</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Essential Reading</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Chapter 40, Hygiene: pp. 915–970</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Clinical Skills</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Performing a Complete or Partial Bed Bath</li>
    <li>Performing a Disposable Bed Bath</li>
    <li>Assisting with a Tub Bath or Shower</li>
    <li>Performing Back Massage</li>
    <li>Performing Perineal Care (Female and Male)</li>
    <li>Making an Unoccupied, Occupied, and Surgical Bed</li>
    <li>Performing Oral Hygiene for an Unconscious Patient</li>
    <li>Cleaning Dentures</li>
    <li>Performing Hair Care and Shampooing in Bed</li>
    <li>Shaving a Male Patient</li>
    <li>Performing Nail and Foot Care</li>
    <li>Assisting with a Gown Change</li>
    <li>HESI: Clinical Nursing Concepts – Dave Mason</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Key Terms</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>CHG:</strong> Chlorhexidine gluconate — antimicrobial used in bathing and oral care.</li>
    <li><strong>VAP:</strong> Ventilator-associated pneumonia — preventable HAI.</li>
    <li><strong>Shear:</strong> Opposing forces that cause skin layers to slide — major contributor to pressure injuries.</li>
    <li><strong>Braden Scale:</strong> Standardized tool to assess pressure injury risk (max score 23; lower = higher risk).</li>
    <li><strong>HOB:</strong> Head of bed.</li>
  </ul>
</Layout>
